its been a rollercoaster of a few weeks, I‚Äôve been really happy, I‚Äôve been really sad, I‚Äôve been everything in between. Some days I didn‚Äôt wanna leave my bed, some days I wanted to make a to do list just to tick everything off twice, some days I ate no vegetables, some days I had 10 portions, some days I went to the gym, most days I did not.  Going through a ‚Äòdown‚Äô phase can be really frustrating when you can‚Äôt justify why you‚Äôre feeling like it. But i guess sometimes thats just the way we feel and sometimes theres not an answer for it. Alls you can to do is crack on, if that means having a few weeks fluctuating between wanting to lay in bed and wanting to the seize the day then so be it.  Sometimes there isn‚Äôt just a quick fix and you might begin to lose the time and energy for things you used to really enjoy, and get scared it never going to come back. Take a break and allow yourself to breathe (never underestimate stress), and then find that energy again because it will come back, you just might be due a few bed days ü•∞ü•≥ but bbes I am BACKKKKKKK #mentalhealthisweird #mentalhealthawareness

my hope for your Christmas 2019 editionü•∞ 
my hope for you this Christmas is you go to dinner parties and catch up brunches  with your friends and family without looking up the restaurant first, my hope is you eat your advent calender everyday in December wondering what shape it‚Äôll be today, my hope is you have a bomb ass breakfast whilst you share your gifts with your loved ones and smile as you receive them, my hope is you will be around the dinner table with your family laughing over the cringe Christmas crackers and not worrying about your dinner, my hope is you keep going back to that crisp bowl because you didn‚Äôt try all the flavours just yet and you fancied another one, my hope is you help your family serve the puddings and grab a quick bite of the mince pies before they are on the table, my hope is you try all the variety of desserts that aunties and cousins have made and you get to tell them how good they are, my hope is when the cheese and biscuits come out you‚Äôre first to jump up with joy even though you are still full from lunch, my hope is you have some mulled wine and dance till you‚Äôre tired till Christmas songs without counting calories in your head. My hope for you this Christmas, is to finish the day with a little bit more chocolate, a tummy full, and a big smile on your face with no regret at all. 
Christmas time can be an extremely hard time for someone suffering with an eating disorder,  this year remember what matters. I promise you, it‚Äôs not the calories in the mince pie that are worth worrying about, but missing out on memories like this is.  Please try and enjoy Christmas time this year. Your life is worth so much more than what your eating disorder is telling you #mentalhealthmatters #afestivefuckofftoeatingdisorders

Figuring out my brain- a series. Episode two: the reflection conundrum 
So if you follow me closely you‚Äôll know I recently did a week without looking at myself - meaning no mirrors, no shiny surfaces, no puddles lmao and no cameras. Now you can look at this and think I‚Äôm being dramatic for what I‚Äôm about to say because its only a week and its just your reflection. But this week sent my emotions up and down and all over the PLACE. The best way I can describe it is have you ever wanted to look at yourself through your friends or partners or families eyes? Have you ever wondered what the difference is between what they see and what you see? Throughout my entire life I‚Äôve asked people what they think I look like, or ‚Äòis this spot obvious‚Äô or ‚Äòdo I look really red‚Äô and 9/10 times the person will tell me I look fine/nice/what are you talking about. AND THEN, 10/10 I will go to the mirror for myself and completely ignore what they had said and attack myself in the mirror for this ‚Äòissue‚Äô I have picked out. This week i couldn‚Äôt do that - my ability to know what I looked like stopped at what my friends said and I couldn‚Äôt contradict them. Now this may be unsurprising, but I felt better in myself because of it.  Without the ability to see *find*  flaws in myself I slowly began to feel them less, and when I was able to look at myself again - I stopped looking for them. Now, obviously this week didn‚Äôt come without issues and somedays I was a pit of anxiety not knowing what I looked like- overall, it was actually quite nice; and a definite EXPERIENCE to say the least. 
Im not saying I‚Äôm going to go on from here a changed human and never see flaws in myself again because thats just not realistic - but it‚Äôs made me more aware than ever before of the negative impacts our brains can have on our well being. Imma stop now because this is just one big ramble and u can just watch my new YT vid ü§™  all‚Äôs I‚Äôm saying - is just think before you attack yourself, because you are the only person that can see it x
